{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cedf60f4-7a5f-4e3a-a355-e2eb417c8fea","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates **`.ips` crash reports** when a process crashes. You can find them in:\n\n1. **`~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — for user-launched apps\n2. **`/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — for system-wide crashes\n\nLook for a file named like `YourAppName_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`.\n\nYou can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them with a GUI.\n\n### Core dumps\n\nmacOS disables core dumps by default. To enable them:\n\n```bash\nsudo sysctl kern.coredump=1\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\n\nCores are written to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n> **Tip:** The `.ips` crash log is usually sufficient — it contains the backtrace, signal info, and loaded libraries. If you need to symbolicate .NET runtime frames in the `.ips` file, I can help with that too.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"14a6c188-55e8-4e18-9eaa-14cad00eec01","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without createdump available. This is a general knowledge question - I don't need to search any codebase. Let me answer directly.","outputTokens":316,"requestId":"6803:32F6A4:18D86AC:1BDFBD7:69FD41A7"},"id":"267a643c-f1f6-4b8a-8d78-1bb7ae1bc997","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:51:43.851Z","parentId":"c5560683-f4f5-4a17-a136-352cd42afb8c"}
